description: {"blocks":[{"key":"e08fi","text":"Protocol for preparing single cells for mass-spec analysis by nPOP as described by Leduc et al., 2021, 2022 DOI: 10.1186/s13059-022-02817-5. nPOP uses piezo acoustic dispensing to isolate individual cells in 300 picoliter volumes and performs all subsequent preparation steps in small droplets on a fluorocarbon-coated slide. This design enables simultaneous sample preparation of thousands of single cells in a single batch. This includes lysing, digesting, and labeling individual cells in volumes below 20 nl. nPOP supports different experimental designs including label free analysis, TMT 18plex with carrier, mTRAQ, and TMT-10plex for TOF instruments (see steps).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":83,"length":24}],"data":{}},{"key":"dtcce","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dhk8f","text":"Data, resources and additional information: https://scp.slavovlab.net/Leduc_et_al_2022 and https://scp.slavovlab.net/nPOP ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":1,"offset":44,"length":42},{"key":2,"offset":91,"length":30}],"data":{}},{"key":"115lq","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6hcr9","text":"Andrew Leduc presented a detailed workflow of nPOP at the 4th Single Cell Proteomics Conference available on YouTube: https://youtu.be/DJ1U_KpMNcY    ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":3,"offset":118,"length":28}],"data":{}},{"key":"2ak2h","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3s8rd","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a2tml","text":"The protocol uses the CellenONE system for liquid handling and cell sorting and assumes basic level of familiarity and training on the CellenONE. If there are any questions, please email leduc.an@northeastern.edu","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8ufe9","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"E4A22DC0B8E811EC82A1A5BB0ADCEB0D","url":"https://doi.org/10.1186/s13059-022-02817-5"}},"1":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"7939267FB8E911ECB45C0A58A9FEAC02","url":"https://scp.slavovlab.net/Leduc_et_al_2022"}},"2":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"EC3F9487B8E911ECB45C0A58A9FEAC02","url":"https://scp.slavovlab.net/nPOP"}},"3":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"00AE1701B8EA11ECB45C0A58A9FEAC02","url":"https://youtu.be/DJ1U_KpMNcY"}}}}

Double click on the target and copy the settings as posted in the picture below:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"d6tn8","text":"  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"6mi9f","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"image","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"2D6608E0B5C111ECAE3B65E23937DA66","height":733,"id":331240,"is_video":false,"legend":"","mime":"image/jpeg","nestedSelector":null,"original_name":"IMG_5839.jpg","placeholder":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrkbiavp.jpg","shadow":false,"source":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdribiavp.jpg","webp_placeholder":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrjbiavp.webp","webp_source":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrhbiavp.webp","width":550}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"c8v7p","text":"Next, we need to make one more target for aspirating samples off of the surface of the glass slide.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"3cspm","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"1dpvi","text":"This should be the exact same as the last one you just made (so make a new duplicate of \"Full_Plate\" and call it \"Full_Plate_SlidePickup\") but the Z Position should be ~29000. This is different on each instrument, so what you can do is go to the Drives tab, move the nozzle to the \"Slides_MetalHolder\" Target area, and inch down the z height so that it is just slightly off the surface of the slide. Once satisfied, set the new value for Z position as you did in step 3.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"gtv5","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"b7o3e","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"ajfbu","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1uf1p","text":"Time to test our new setup! In the main tab, select your Target area to be \"Full_Plate\" and the run to \"SpotRun\".  Then load the following Field file: System_setup \u003e Setup_slide_all.fld. This method should place a small droplet in all 4 corners of each slide. If you're not happy with droplet positions, you can adjust the spacing in between slides with the parameter shown below. After changing it, be sure to hit ALL to apply the spacing to for the distance between each slide. Once this is set, you will need to apply these settings to all the field files that you use (load everything and save them with the changes you made to these parameters).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"9sbv6","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6jvjj","text":"To get started, you will need a few things. These consumables can all be purchased from Scienion","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":88,"length":8}],"data":{}},{"key":"f8rn8","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fpkv2","text":"Personally, I have had the most success operating with two PDC nozzles from Scienion:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"58tif","text":" A regular glass PDC, size medium, for handling cells ","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"47jur","text":"A PDC 70 with coating type 2. This is for handling organic solvents such as DMSO and protein mixtures. ","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2hilj","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"eruq6","text":"If you do not have the type two coating nozzle, my advice is to still use two regular glass nozzles, leaving one for DMSO, and the other for trypsin and cells. If you only have one nozzle, it may require multiple flush steps when switching back and forth between organic and aqueous.  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"c55uj","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"498c6","text":"You can also use 2 PDC 70 nozzles, that works just fine.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6s5g2","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6d8ap","text":"For slides, we use the H1 slides which are regular glass slides that have a flourocarbon coating. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":1,"offset":23,"length":9}],"data":{}},{"key":"doah5","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3cdog","text":"In terms of the sample prep itself, you will need your cells, DMSO, 1M TEAB(triethylammonium bicarbonate), Trypsin Gold, Benzonase endonuclease, DDM (n-Dodecyl-beta-Maltoside), HEPES pH 8.5, any labeling reagents (TMT, mTRAQ, etc.), and triethylammonium bicarbonate (TEAB) if using mTRAQ.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"UNDERLINE","offset":174,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dh84s","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"9B387DD9B78811ECB45C0A58A9FEAC02","url":"https://www.scienion.com/products/sciconsumables"}},"1":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"3573A040976311EDBF3AD3AC7E9BC73E","url":"https://shop.scienion.com/consumables/scienion/slides-and-plates/16/scichip?number="}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"bel0b","text":"Once you have everything you need to get started, it's worth investing some time to get your workflow ironed out prior to attempting a full prep.  In the following two sub-points you will find some preparatory steps that I take alongside some troubleshooting suggestions.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1jsbv","text":"Getting the nozzles in the exact same condition each time you start a prep. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":76}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"1gq75","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"a9nn1","text":"My routine is to use the syringe attachment to clean and flush the nozzle and lines within the PDC. I place the tip of the PDC in water that is sonicating and pull water in and out of the PDC for ~5 minutes, followed by a minute of 100% ethanol and then another minute of water. Be careful not to get the black ring of the PDC wet, as this can cause electronics to short if you use directly after.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"3itve","text":"  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"9r7ic","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"7ktlb","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"image","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"5189A140B61711ECAE3B65E23937DA66","height":733,"id":331244,"is_video":false,"legend":"","mime":"image/jpeg","nestedSelector":null,"original_name":"Image from iOS (14).jpg","placeholder":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrqbiavp.jpg","shadow":false,"source":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrnbiavp.jpg","webp_placeholder":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrpbiavp.webp","webp_source":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrmbiavp.webp","width":550}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"3f4lh","text":"Practice with the reagents you will be using before starting a prep. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":69}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"88qis","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"ftsqp","text":"Several factors such as humidity, room temperature and the specific nozzle can have large effects on dispensing accuracy. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"cc3ob","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"dfj93","text":"As an example, for dispensing mTRAQ labels, I use DMSO as I found it easiest to work with, however, we have also used Ethanol and IPA for dispensing mTRAQ in the past. This can work well, but, requires you to aspirate air and then ~20 uL of organic solvent prior to aspirating label and dispensing. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"a4uhv","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"272el","text":"Some tips that have worked for me:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"1hnng","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"7l2vd","text":"1) the trypsin is highly viscous, so be sure to run \"dip wash\" after aspirating, and reduce frequency, voltage, and pulse considerably","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"dedte","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"e8sde","text":"2) if a droplet seems to be shooting off to the side, dabbing the bottom of the tip twice with a kimwipe (damp with ethanol) can really help. If the issue persists, move nozzle to home position, turn on continuous dispensing, and try cleaning tip with an ethanol-dampened kimwipe for ~60 seconds.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"3oe88","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"f7f6o","text":"3) Generally higher voltage has helped with DMSO dispensing. Also make sure humidity is not too high when dispensing DMSO, this can cause droplets to stick to the end of nozzle. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"1g0gt","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Carrier and Reference Preparation (***Only if Carrier is used***)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"fotm5","text":"Prepare cell pellets of at least 500,000 cells for all relevant cell types . Add 100% DMSO to cells to a cellular concentration of 6000 cells/ul. Incubate cells in DMSO for 20 minutes to lyse cells. Add mass spectrometry grade water to bring solution to 2000 cells/ul. More information on carrier and reference preparation is available at Petelski, A.A., Emmott, E., Leduc, A.et al.Multiplexed single-cell proteomics using SCoPE2. Nat Protoc 16,5398–5425 (2021).https://doi.org/10.1038/s41596-021-00616-z ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":376,"length":6},{"style":"italic","offset":431,"length":11},{"style":"bold","offset":442,"length":3}],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":462,"length":42}],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"31E63D35B8EB11ECB45C0A58A9FEAC02","url":"https://doi.org/10.1038/s41596-021-00616-z"}}}}

steps.section: Carrier and Reference Preparation (***Only if Carrier is used***)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"aihdh","text":"Add 1x benzonase, 100mM TEAB and 20 ng/uL of trypsin. Digest sample at 37 degrees C overnight. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Carrier and Reference Preparation (***Only if Carrier is used***)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"4qg6r","text":"Label carrier and reference samples with desired labels. Dilute samples before combining such that the composite sample is at 200 cells/uL of carrier and 5 cells/uL of reference.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1dcri","text":"Follow start-up procedure for CellenONE with two nozzles attached. In the far left position, attach a size medium glass PDC nozzle. In the adjacent slot to the right, attach a size medium PDC 70 nozzle with type 2 coating.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"dh3j1","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"9lqfv","text":"  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"2crop","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"image","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"CBB93B90F07B11EB9C3AD501F62B8F4D","height":410,"id":331248,"is_video":false,"legend":"","mime":"image/png","nestedSelector":null,"original_name":"Screen Shot 2021-07-29 at 10.46.25 AM.png","placeholder":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrubiavp.jpg","shadow":false,"source":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrsbiavp.jpg","webp_placeholder":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrtbiavp.webp","webp_source":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrrbiavp.webp","width":550}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"43p8e","text":"In the target spotting location, place the glass slide holder (make sure it fits well) and then place your fluorocarbon-coated glass slides (CellenONE H1 Slides) in their designated slots (make sure they are all level). ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"43n0k","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"2rdnv","text":"In the probe location, place any desired 384 well plate for storing and pickup of cell suspensions and reagents used in sample preparation. On the CellenONE \"Main\" tab, set the probe location to the relevant 384 well plate and set the target location to our new \"Full_plate\".","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"6r9os","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"k547","text":"  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"9m6th","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"image","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"96201260F07B11EB9C3AD501F62B8F4D","height":733,"id":331252,"is_video":false,"legend":"","mime":"image/jpeg","nestedSelector":null,"original_name":"slides.jpg","placeholder":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrybiavp.jpg","shadow":false,"source":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrwbiavp.jpg","webp_placeholder":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrxbiavp.webp","webp_source":"https://content.protocols.io/files/kdrvbiavp.webp","width":550}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"60dqs","text":"Suspend cells in 1X PBS at a concentration of 200-300 cells/uL. If cells are prone to clumping, first filter with a 40 micron filter to ensure a fast pace of cell sorting.
